      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Carl Sandburg (1878-1967) was an American author, editor and poet.  He won three Pulitzer prizes, two for his poetry and the third 
		for his biography of Abraham Lincoln.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Carl Sandburg Collection</emph> consists of three items of outgoing correspondence and a manuscript.    
			Two letters are to John Stuart Groves.  The third, written on the letterhead stationery of the <emph render="italic">Chicago Daily 
			News</emph>, is a note to Miss Cooper about her Memphis bookshop.  It includes a holograph attachment which reads in part:</p>
			
			<blockquote><p>It is a booklover's tavern; ancient; shrewd; up to date; on the job; careless; lavish; paradoxical  &amp; whimsical; 
			its welcomes are fresh as the freshest eggs; the panels of its doors have passwords for all book bugs...Whether you laugh or pray 
			depends on how you feel.</p></blockquote>
			
      <p>Titled "Preface," the seven-page typescript was written in 1924 as an early version of Sandburg's introduction to 
		<emph render="italic">The Prairie Years</emph>.  In broadcasts on radio and national television, the piece was read by Sandburg on 
		Abraham Lincoln's birthday, February 12th, 1954.</p></scopecontent>
      
      <arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
         <head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
         <p>Letters are in chronological order.</p>
      </arrangement>
      
